segments.text: I can't say that.
Well, anyway, the drownouts were interesting, too, because people would sneak in the dorm, usually through the steam tunnels, come up into the dorm.
And we'd get word of that sometimes, getting me to be drowned out.
And so we'd have people watch in, but they'd get by.
Go to the top floor and pull as many of those valves on cracker heads off of those commodes.
And, of course, water just went everywhere.
You get up on the top floor of this third and fourth floor of the dorm and pull those off.
Before you know it, water would be cascading down those stairs.
And I'll never forget as long as I live, one time they had so much water coming down the steps, probably 2.30, 3 o'clock in the morning.
I saw a New Testament cascading down the steps.
It came almost to the foot of my door.
When you're in a water fight, you try to get everything up off the floor.
You try to get it up on the bunk or your desk or something because it would run.
But that was kind of fun.
Whose job was it then to clean up after the water fight?
Well, of course we cleaned our own room, and I think we got out and cleaned the halls too.
We didn't have janitors.
We didn't have phones in the dorms.
You know, we didn't have the amenities that you would have today in the dorm.
Concrete floors.
I mean, somebody might get a throw rug or an area rug in their room, but most of us didn't have anything like that.
So that you knew pretty well.
If we make the mess, we're going to clean it up.
Oh, everybody had prunes.
You'd start sweeping water and you'd just keep on, and of course there's debris, you know, waste paper and junk, like you say, stuff came down the steps or whatever.
But it wasn't unusual to do that.
Another thing that was common was you'd start dumping stuff in a big one.
It was a great big butt can, big old ash, I mean, big old waste paper cans outside in the dorms.
You'd start filling it with water and filling it with old milk and,
scraps, and cigarette ashes, and probably against the door.
The door's open to the inside.
So if somebody you really were kind of chapped at or somebody, you know, everybody's picking all over you, lean that up against it.
Of course, when you open the door, that big thing would fall over and just flood the room with just debris and junk and the most disgusting things.
Now, was that also called a drowned out?
No, and I don't know what that was called, but I remember it was done fairly often.
Did y'all have any kind of, you or your friends have any kind of joke you played on somebody that was going to have a special big date?
I have to admit to you, the non-regs did not have big special events like the boot dance and the military ball and the cotton ball.
We didn't participate as much.
A great regret in our life.
But we didn't participate in that to that extent, so it was not common.
About the most we would do would be to have a date night for football games or something like that.
Parents weekend was, I think, Mother's Day, it was called.
Mother's Day, maybe, or something like that.
It was not Parents Day, I don't think.
And that's the only day, as I recall, that mothers or women could come into the arms.
Do you ever remember any good bull in a class, in a lab, in an academic area?
probably took studies too seriously because of intimidation by probation or whatever, something like that, that I don't remember an awful lot that went on.
Chemistry, there was always a goof off.
You'd always mess up somebody's experiment or hand you something that was a little too warm or hot to handle or something like that, but I don't remember a lot.
Let's slide to academics.
Try to recall for us some of the
very important, in terms of your life, important faculty members, advisors, counselors, who were they?
What was special about them?
Well, that's a great topic.
Probably from a standpoint of significance.
I told you that I went home every weekend to see this little head major head over there.
When you didn't get out of class until then on Saturday, and you had to be back in class on Monday, and you lived 160 miles away, and you hitchhiked, that was not a real good arrangement.
Mid-semester, my grades came out, and they showed that I went to Tyler every year.
Dr. Potts.
Wonderful man.
Dr. R.C.
Potts.
Got to know him on a personal basis.
In those days, you didn't have dorm phones.
And when you had a note on your door, the color of the note determined what to do.
You had a phone call with the YMCA at home.
or there was a note behind your name, get a name card, you know, card holders, and they'd stick those notes in there.
Certain colored notes, don't know which color, maybe yellow or something, meant you needed to go see somebody, faculty.
Dr. Potts left one of those, and I had sent one, a runner over there, and left that, and I got that in, of course, had butterflies on the scene.
I walked in there, and we got the most pleasant visit about common friends, mutual friends that we had in Tyler, great Aggies in Tyler.
He leaned forward and looked me in the eye.
He said, young man, if you intend to get your degree from this institution, I suggest you hook yourself into the traces.
That is a direct quote.
That almost makes me cry.
He changed my life.
I told him later.
Now, in doing that, he was doing that in his role as the College of Agriculture.
That's correct.
The Wildlife Department was in the College of Agriculture.
It scared me to death, embarrassed me horrendously.
Think back.
Had he not done that, I wouldn't have personal interest in that.
And had the way that he did was settling me down to where I had some respect for him and not mad at him.
then I don't know how to respond.
I was a sensitive enough guy to word and serious enough about my studies until I got into goofing off.
Until it embarrassed me.
Now my roommate had a similar call, the guy that went to A&M with me from my same community.
He said, oh, you won't fly because they won't do that.
He finished with Stephen at Boston.
He didn't make it.
He didn't hold on.
I got back and pouted for a day.
Wrote the girl a letter and told her I would not be coming home much anymore and got serious about my studies and of course it turned everything around.
I saw Dr. Potts years later on the field at TCU at a football game and he was working helping the athletic department I think after retirement.
And I told my wife, I've got to go see him.
And I went down there to the field and I told him what we'd done.
I said, do you remember that?
He said, son, I've had that experience many times.
I don't.
But I'm glad it worked out well for you.
I was a veterinarian by that time.
Because I went back to school six years after I'd been out.
But that was the most significant thing that happened.
But I remember those guys.
Dr. Scruggs.
Snuggs is his name.
Over in chemistry.
He was a World War I veteran.

somebody, remember he was a flying ace or something, tough son of a gun, Dr. Pierce, Mr. Pierce, he wasn't a doctor, we called him Dr. Pierce, Mr. Pierce in the English department, he taught speaking for professional men, and he would call on you cold turkey, come to the front of the room, and call on you, tell us about so and so, and make you do impromptu speeches, demonstration speeches and so on, and I have to tell you that anybody who had his course,
may be intimidated when they get up and talk, but the less intimidated wouldn't have been had they not had his course.
Now, did y'all have nicknames for him?
Oh, didn't have one.
I don't know whether Pierce did or not.
Snuggs was just Snuggs.
Now, if he caught you doing something, if you're smoking, come in the classroom, he'd collect cigarettes.
He had a huge collection of cigarettes, you know, because you'd give him one.
But there were many nicknames.
Ivy League, Taylor.
Did you have class with him?
I didn't have him.
I had another guy for history, and I'm sitting here, and I can normally think of his name, and I can't remember his name.
Delightful fellow.
Taught a good course.
Got an old blue book benton.
Taught government.
Tough professor.
Essay questions.
It was not rare to see 20s and 30s on test scores.
He scared me to death.
He scared good grade into me.
I studied that course as much as maybe any other undergraduate course I ever studied.
Chemistry didn't scare me enough.
I had a tough time, but chemistry didn't take it seriously.
When I went back to go to med school, I had to take some chemistry.
I was a good chemistry student, but there again it was a matter of application.
Do you remember who the chemistry instructors were at your head?
A guy named Smintowski taught me one time, but he taught me after I went back to school.
A guy named, for some reason I'm really having trouble with names this morning, Isabel.
Dr. Isabel taught over there.
He's the one that did that, invented that imitation skunk.
I wouldn't be surprised.
For deer hunting.
Really?
Yeah.
He was a hunter.
I remember he was a hunter.
What you do to get so the deer doesn't smell you, he smells his imitation skunk smell that won't stick with you when you go home.
And you take a little of that and rub it on where you're going to be.
Yeah.
Any other nicknames you remember?
Well...
The nickname, we had some special names for Gunny Putnam that taught economics.
Hard-nosed, got to embarrass you, move you to the front of the class and embarrass you.
Every Monday you'd get a new one, got to pick on him.
Don't remember his official nickname.
There were some, C.S.
Harris, Ivy League Taylor, Dr. Dan the Great Point Man.
I didn't have him.
I think I should have, but...
I know some people who said that without him, they would never have their ring or degrees.
Dan Russell.
But in terms of...
The wildlife department, of course, I remember those professors well.
They didn't have nicknames for them.
Who were some of them?
Dr. Baldoff taught fisheries and herpetology.
Dr. Davis, W.B.
Davis, was a pretty renowned mammologist, and he was the head of the department.
Dr. Jack Inglis.
was there.
Dr. Dixon was there, but I didn't know him.
He was teaching.
I think he must have come after I took those basic courses.
Describe Baldolph and Inglis.
Tough-minded professors.
Dr. Davis didn't laugh a lot.
Talked about antics in the classroom.
Studied for labs.
That wildlife curriculum was very challenging, correctly.
very scientific taxonomic studies and memory had to be pretty extensive.
You really had to work on it because it was just raw, rank memory.
Just hundreds and hundreds and hundreds of scientific names and stuff.
Dr. Davis was a dictatorial type head of the department.
And he didn't mix with the students all that much.
But everybody scared the death out of him.
And one time we were studying for a mammology
And we had these dried skins.
And he had maybe the world's best bat collection, certainly the one in the southwest.
But there were skins where the bats had extended wings.
And a guy named Friedersdorf decided he was going to sail one of those like a plane over to another student.
And about the time that he sailed that bat, Dr. Davis walked around the corner.
In typical A&M fashion in those days, we all paid a big price for this.
We had a practical on the spot.
Dr. Baldoff, a fellow that at the time you were kind of afraid of, because he was really, by the book, a tough professional, very demanding, good sense of humor, really good sense of humor.
As I began to finish up my studies and look back on him, I thought a world of him.
He forced you into...
He forced you into being a pretty good student because he challenged it.
He would give those, in those days, he'd give those 200-point tests.
Lab practicals were just absolutely dismal because you'd have them at night sometime and they went on forever.
And those were extremely challenging.
All right, when you got your degree and you're going out into the real world, how well prepared did you feel you were for that real world based on your A&M training?
Technically speaking, I felt very, very equipped.

But right after, when I went on active duty, I went to Fort Knox, Kentucky, at very light duty, worked in a separation transfer point, and I was a clerk, had a Class 8 pass, we came in with no formations and that sort of thing.
That environment set up a very casual social atmosphere for those that worked in that particular transfer center.
I met a man who went to Wayne in Michigan, a fellow who went to New York University, and so on.
My liberal arts experience, my experience with politics, my experience with the world around us,
Frankly, it was extremely lucky.
I couldn't carry on a decent conversation with those fellows about current events, about the world scene politically or the local situation.
Social aspects, socially I was dwarfed.
quite frankly.
You know, I didn't have anything but maybe a couple pairs of pants, you know, two shirts or something up there.
These fellas came from people with better financial backgrounds than I did too.
But at the same time, I have to tell you that I thought, I realized then I had a lot to learn.
I was determined to do that too, by the way.
I spent a lot of time with those guys.
Let's see, did you feel as a transfer student, did you ever feel like
you were looked down upon or second class or anything like that?
At the time, non-regs was not a very complimentary term because most were in the Corps.
And the one that wanted to be in the Corps, you wouldn't transfer in the Corps when you're a junior.
I'm not sure you even could.
But it was impractical to do that, even if you could.
But anyway, yeah, I have to tell you that I did feel that way.
And right now, when somebody asks what I feel that you have,
It's a question I almost dread because there's an explanation who was with it, you know.
Now, I'm here to tell you the transfer students, I don't think I'm a living example, can be as dedicated an Aggie as anybody ever lived, more than many who were in the Corps.
I was going to say.
But with the same token, if you say, do you wish it would have been differently?
Absolutely.
Because I've had a rich life because of A&M.
I would have had a richer life had I been in the Corps, and I fully recognize that.
This is not really part of this, but how many association presidents have not been corps members?
Not many.
I don't know.
I'm not sure.
Has there ever been a transfer student to the corps?
That's what I'm thinking.
But I have to say that in my stock answer, if somebody gave me the trouble and said, well, what about a transfer?
That was not exactly the same.
He was a transfer student.
And I would stand on it.
Also, once or twice, Mr.
Rudder, to me, let me know that he had a little bit of a thin spot of having frogged in.
That one he didn't like.
He didn't like anybody to gig him on that.
I tried my very best to transfer him after my freshman year at Tyler Junior College.
My buddy and I were on the transfer very badly.
It just wasn't going to work at home.
And I worked all the time.
I was in junior college.
But like I say, we needed this.
We needed the financial support.
Our whole family did.
Part of my check went to make a car payment.
And that's just the way it was in those days.
And I missed a lot.
And I realize it.
I would not say that I'm thin-skinned about it.
Well, I guess I would be thin-skinned about it.
But it's not by somebody else.
It's self-imposed.
Do you remember what, in round numbers, what it cost for you to go to A&M?
Yes, sir.
It cost me somewhere between $800 and $1,000 a year.
And that's room, board, tuition?
That's the whole ballpark.
Of course, you didn't have cards.
I spent a nickel one week out of pocket.
I was going to hitchhike home, and I had a nickel on Monday.
Now, I'm not saying I didn't have anything but a nickel, but it was a principle.
I'm going to spend a nickel this week.
And I bought a Coke on the way out of the dorm to go hitchhike with Tom.
All right.
I've had some people describe hitchhiking in the 30s.
Tell me about hitchhiking in the 50s.
Where did you go to catch the ride?
Well, you try to get it out on 21.
You get some kind of ride.
Usually it was some Aggie leaving town.
Now, many times you could post something over an academic door that you needed to ride to the tower.
Sometimes it didn't work out.
Everybody didn't have a car.
Far, far fewer people had cars.
And a few of the guys that had cars were screwy as a loon.
They'd drive 95 miles an hour down those old roads up through the North Suge and, you know, all through Baird and Skirman half the day.
So you'd hitchhike at a matter of convenience.

Once you got out there with that suitcase, that big TAM on it, it wasn't a TAM, it's a big T, Texas Aggies on it, or that little maroon bag that everybody had, little cloth maroon bag, Texas Aggies on there.
When you got out there, if you'd stay on the beaten paths, hitchhiking was not a problem.
You would get picked up.
Now, you didn't want to go off like I did one time to Hearn, over to Marquis, to Graveland, to, you know, that'd take you, you'd grow old doing that.
And I've had rides with drunks and, you know, women and, you know, everything else.
It was an experience that I wouldn't want to trade it, but I could see where people would particularly want to do it.
You couldn't do it today.
Normally, it took you how long to get from college?
Not much longer.
If you caught a ride, you could usually be home in about three hours if you caught a ride.
you know, within three hours.
You'd be there in three to four hours.
Now sometimes five, but I mean usually it did not take you that much longer.
You could stay on the beaten path, and I'm talking about my way would be go up to Normandy, cut across over there, and get up on 69, you know, and head up toward Palestine, Palestine to Tyler.
There was not much to it.
It's coming back, by the way.
You know, the Aggie line was out.
Every town had a place called the Aggie line.
And that's where Aggies would be trying to get back to school.
I mean, I was sitting in laps, you know, laying down across people and everything else, setting floorboards.
If there was room for a person in the car, you would not be left there at the Aggie line.
And in that routine, class...
year, civilian or corps, did not matter.
Is that right?
In hitchhiking?
No.
Now Buck Henderson tells me that he used to catch a ride with Rod Stepp and some of those guys back up there and they never even dropped pounds with him.
He used to ride back and forth.
They never dropped pounds with him until the very end of his freshman year.
And he never could figure that one out.
They were harassing him.
But no, that's right.
That was insignificant.
You were Aggie buddies and that was not a problem.
Did you have a job while you were at ANA?
I did not work regularly.
I helped some over at the wildlife department.
I talked to Mr. Rhodes who was over at the forestry about working there.
We helped him some, but not much of a job regularly.
I was normally had a schedule with labs to where it didn't allow much.
In the summer, where did you work?
Well, in the summer what you tried to do, this is an interesting thing, you talked about $800 to $1,000 a year to go to school.
Of course, I couldn't make $800 to $1,000 in the summer.
So I'd work and make up all the debt, pay back the bank as much as I could, and then they'd start borrowing again.
So by the time I got to my senior year, I borrowed most of my last year down there, my third year.
In the summers, I was fortunate because Tyler State Park was where I had grown up, and I had, by that time, had a pretty good handle on that.
And I'd go back, and I knew how to work all those stations, the boathouse, concession area, the bathhouse, the lake and swimming areas.
I'd go back and help my dad and work there.
And in that particular case, nepotism served people that well because you knew the job well.
And you would work tremendous hours, get up very early, make the garbage runs, the picnic areas, and work until closing time at 1 o'clock, clean the buildings and so on.
Go home and do the laundry and the bathing suits sometime at 1 o'clock in the morning.
One summer, I worked with the quail hatchery in Tyler.
Being a classmate in wildlife, they wanted you to have a summer job with the quail hatchery.
So when you finished, you owed about how much?
Probably over $800.
The reason I ask that, I'm comparing that to the sums of today.
Right.
And of course, today some of them have staggering amounts.
Well, I only make $340 a month when I cut it out.
Sure.
Now, I'm not suggesting that it's equitable.
So you owed between two and three months income.
That's right.
Let's see.
Go back to the classroom.
What were the expected rules?
of class attendance, behavior, attitude, dress, etc.
Well, attendance was stressed to the extent that if you were graduating senior, if you cut classes, we of course had so many I think, if you cut classes, you did not graduate.
Not you may not graduate, you did not graduate.
That was stressed.
You didn't take finals if you had a C average or better, I think it was, in your senior year, but you had to go to class and they were very emphatic.
I know friends
I know people who never finished A&M because they end that far along in their studies they did not finish because they were kicked out twice in a so-called last semester.
The dress was, of course, military or non-reg.
I typically wore jeans and probably some plaid shirt, you know, Margal socks, plaid shirt, jeans, and probably some kind of a fetal boot, you know, some kind.
Didn't wear tennis shoes, didn't wear shorts.
Umbrellas were not done at A&M.
You wouldn't dare carry an umbrella across the area.
You should.
Yes.
Everybody should.
And I remember graduate students maybe didn't or something, but you spoke to everybody, non-reg or whatever.
Now, every once in a while you'd find some guy that didn't speak, and you know, they were outcast to the hilt.
But you spoke to everybody.
If you saw somebody in there, just like you were in the court, you went back and you shook hands with who they were with on the side wall.
It was not an exception.
There were very, very few exceptions in our school.
What about student diversity?
Tell me about any acquaintances you recall who were not mainline Anglo-Saxon.
For example, were there some Jewish students that you remember?
I'm sure there were.
Tyler and it was white and black over there and there was some Jewish guys never even thought about it you know.
Were there any any Hispanic students?
Yeah there were some Hispanic students there not they didn't stick out they were just students that were there there wasn't no issue was made of that you see what I'm saying?
Right across the hall was a guy from Raymondville
a Caucasian guy, a white male student, white student, and a guy from Raymondville, Hispanic descent.
I didn't think any more or less of one than I did the other.
Just no issue was made.
Now, the nearest thing you would come to finding someone would be maybe a student from Pakistan, Panama.
But you know, we were personable.
We knew those guys.
And nothing was made of that issue in those days that I know of.
That would be my answer, too.
It was not an issue that we bothered to give any thought to.
If you said, where's that guy from Panama?
Now, faculty members had nicknames.
Did students in that era have nicknames?
A lot did, in the core they all did, just about.
But a lot of guys, I guess, had nicknames.
But in those days, no matter whether you're A&M or not, a lot of people had nicknames.
My best friend was Heavy, and my other best friend was, my two best friends were Pinky.
They called me Ace.
You know, my middle initial's A for Allen, and they called me Ace.
And still do.
I get letters A's across there or something.
But it was not unusual.
People had nicknames a lot in those days.
YMCA.
Uh-huh.
What happened at the Y in those days?
Well, my experience at the Y was where you went to, you were summoned to go to the farm.
And my granddad passed away when I was a senior then.
And he had several crises when I was a senior.
And I hitchhiked home, left as early as 4 o'clock in the morning before leaving, trying to get my time.
And he'd respond, he'd come back and do fine for a while.
but you'd have a knock on the door and they'd bring you a telephone message from the YMCA.
Yale practices were held on steps of the YMCA.
After the ball game, the Yale leaders would go to the YMCA.
The financial aid office was over there, if I remember down in the basement.
Housing I think was over in the basement of the YMCA building.
All right.
Meetings.
We had hometown club meetings many times there or anything in that city.
What did a hometown club do?
That was really the social organization outside the Corps of Cadets.
And I'm not saying the Corps was excluded from that, but non-regs corps everybody.
Hometowns were a big thing.
Tyler Smith County A&M Club.
Hometown club was a big thing.
We gathered, and I don't remember, I doubt if it was monthly, but it was quarterly.
Mother's clubs would send cookies.
I was an officer in that club.
They'd send cookies, and I'd get the cookies, and I'd go to the post office and get them.
Post office was a big thing in those days.
Everybody would go to the post office.
Went over and had a box of cookies, and I had trouble keeping them up somewhere where the ants didn't get in them until we had our meeting.
And probably did what?
Probably MSC or somebody had an urn of coffee or something up there, and I'd take the cookies over at our meetings.

The greatest party that was given in Tyler, Texas in those days was A&M Hometown Club party at Christmas break and students, mainly A&M, the girls in Tyler wanted to go to that so we had no trouble getting dates.
We had a disc jockey out there, clean fun, people drank, brought their bottles or something, like Dry Counties.
Sponsored by the A&M Club?
And the Mothers Club helping?
Mothers Club and the local A&M Club, Tyler Smith County, and the students would go.
Many students from other universities would come to that party.
A great, great party, you know, up there.
Clean-cut thing, but we had a lot of fun.
And whatever happened to it, I don't know.
MSC.
Describe.
Well, it's got the nickname of the living room on the campus.
I don't know whether they still call that or not.
In those days, it was just that.
Dorms were small, but they were pretty smart.
When you want to meet somebody, or if you're ever going to do something where you needed a cup of coffee or something like that, you go to the MSC.
The Bowling Alley was down there.
I wasn't a bowler, but when you rarely had a date on the campus, they'd always want to go down to Bowling Alley.
That's where everybody gathered and you'd see your friends down there.
If they weren't so good looking, you'd try not to go to Bowling Alley.
But you'd go to the MSC and down there, the Association of Former Students was down there and down the hall.
I guess it would be the West End down there, downstairs.
They had a small library over there.
A lot of their hometown newspapers would be there and publications.
Periodicals were there.
Read those.
Along the main walk right now where the chairs and sitting areas with the windows, they were there in those days.
A lot of foreign students spent time at the NSC.
I say we didn't delineate that, but I do remember that it was not unusual for a lot of the foreign students to spend time over there.
Also, that's where you can make your phone calls.
If you want to call home, you go downstairs, down that hallway, kind of like you're going to the MSC, I'm sorry, the Associated Department of Students Office.
On the left-hand side there was a bank of phones.
And if you want to make a phone call, you'd go back, get in line, and call home or something.
Guyon Hall.
What happened in and around Guyon Hall?
Well, it's the end of the walk down there, and Guyon Hall was the most interesting place I guess there was.
The cadets would go there and watch, you know, there'd be productions over there of some kind.
The big productions were at G. Raleigh, Blacktown Hall.
I didn't go there a lot, but you know how the students were always wisecracking and talking back and comments and responding.
Going to a movie at Aggieland those days was an experience to behold.
You may not hear much dialogue at the movie.
You heard a lot of conversation outside the audience.
Really a fun time.
Funny, some of the original comments you heard.
Were there movies almost every night at Guyon?
I don't remember.
I'm not sure there were movies every night at Guyon.
Maybe on the weekends.
I do go to Guy a lot.
I've been there, been there a number of times.
I don't remember going a lot to Guy.
The town halls are much more memorable to me because they had big name entertainment in there.
Swan Lake, saw Swan Lake there.
Brenda Lee was there.
Gosh, the Lettermen, you know, they were a popular singing group in those days.
They came.
And it was almost like you'd have a feeling that the, you know, when you went in the military, they had these USOs, these shows sometimes.
It was a great time being there, but there was some melancholy when it was over.
When the town halls were over, it was a little bit melancholic, and you'd been to a great thing, but it was such an uplifting experience that when it was over, it became fairly mundane.
And I'll tell you what, that was a love-hate relationship if I ever saw it.
You'd leave that campus, and you could not wait to leave that campus.
You'd drive back in there on Sunday nights, especially when it was winter, and you'd see those old smokestacks over there and that steam coming out.
it looked like a penitentiary.
That big water tower.
It felt like a penitentiary.
But there's something about that that bonded us that I don't know anybody has really ever explained to me where I fully understand that emotion.
But it's an emotional thing to talk about.
There's a spirit that can never be told.
I'm telling you.
